    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.45_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">4</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        814 Emerson Avenue, North
                        Minneapolis 11
                        January 12, 1957
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Here we are now penetrating seriously the second half of the 20th century! 1957! And, if Dewey Beard has died (I don't know that he has), not a single participant left from the Custer Fight! The last Union Army soldier died in Minnesota last year, I think. A few Confederate soldiers still live, I guess. They must feel, no doubt, a responsbility to outlive the Yankees, so vigorously does the gall still float. Badger Clark hasn't written me in almost two years, and I don't know how his fortunes prosper. Soon you, Mr. Neihardt, will be ripe enough to be considered an old-timer!! And don't think I have forgotten that I can say already that I know a man who knew a man who knew another man that had slept at a campfire with Jed Smith!</p>
                
                <p>The most important bit of news from our household is the arrival on December 23 of our first baby, Emily Dickinson Lemons. She is a little beauty, naturally and she has taken over the household with all the vigor of her little red clutching body. At times <del>We</del><add>I</add> wish we could subject her to the discipline of a cradleboard, so tyrannical are her cries.</p>
                
                <p>Her name you wil note. I like the old American custom of naming babies after favorite and significant people--rather than the cursed modern habit of naming children after the "cute" personalities in the movies. Now Emily Dickinson was a rare spirit, as I know. If Emily had been a boy, we were prepred to name him "Frank Bennett Fiske Lemons." Frank and Emily, a pair, huh?</p>
                
                <p>How are the Neihardts these days? Must be fun living in the old quiet Missouri community of Columbia, on your farm on the hill. Daniel Boone's last home, you know--near Columbia. Did you read that fine biography of him by John Bakeless? Came out in 1947. Well, we're tired--mighty tired--of this apartment living in cramped quarters with neighbors' noises all the time. As Badger Clark says,</p>
                
                <lg><l>I loved my fellow man the best</l>
                <l>When he was scattered some.</l></lg>
                
                <p>But this should be the last year of this university life. I'm becoming by this time quite hostile to acad<del>a</del><add>e</add>mic life and to the gray sickness of literary criticism. But if I can finish this Ph. D. we'll be able to do some things we want to do.</p>
                
                <p>Hope everybody at Skyrim is well and happy--</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Love,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Bill Lemons</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
                
                
